                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              Alana has to take $10 \ \text{millilitres}$ of medicine three times a day. How long would a $180 \ \text{millilitre}$ bottle last her?

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              As per the question,

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              She has to take $10 \ \text{ml}$ medicine three times a day.

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              It means $3 \times 10 = 30 \ \text{ml}$ per day.

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              Quantity of medicine $= 180 \ \text {ml}$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              $ \begin{aligned} &= \dfrac {180} {30} \\ &= \dfrac {6 \times 30} {30} \\ &= \dfrac {6 \times \cancel {30}} {\cancel {30}} \\ &= 6 \end{aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              medicine will last for $6$ days.

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              $6$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              Tomasc adds the same number to $23$ and to $8$ so that the first is then double the second. What was the number he used?

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              Let the number $=x$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              $ \begin{aligned} 23 + x &= 2 \times (8 + x) \\ 23 + x &= 16 + 2x \\ 2x - x &= 23 - 16 \\ x &= 7 \end{aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              The number is $7$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              $7$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              My father was $31$ on my $8 \text{th}$ birthday. How old will he be on my $30 \text{th}$ birthday?

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              As per the question,

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              Father's age on my $8 \text{th}$ birthday $= 31$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              Father's age on my $30 \text {th}$ birthday $= 31 + (30 - 8)$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              $ \begin{aligned} &= 31 + (30 - 8) \\ &= 31 + 22 \\ &= 53 \end{aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              Father's age on my $30 \text {th}$ birthday $= 53$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              In a Latin test, Suril got $6$ times as many marks as Krishan. Ashwini has twice as many as Krishan.

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              Ashiwini got $30$ marks. How many marks did Suril get?

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              Let Krishan got $x$ marks.

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              As per the question,

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              Suril got $6x$ marks.

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              Ashwini got $30$ marks which is equal to $2 \times$ Krishan's marks.

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              $ \begin{aligned} 2 \times x &= 30 \\ x &= \dfrac {30} {2} \\ x &= \dfrac {2 \times 15} {2} \\ x &= \dfrac {\cancel {2} \times 15} {\cancel {2}} \\ x &= 15 \end{aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              Suril got $6 \times 15 = 90$ marks.

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              $90$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              Morose's team has lost $3$ times as many matches as they have won.

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              They have not drawn any matches. They have played $24$ matches.

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              How many matches they have won?

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              Let the number of matches they won $= x$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              As per the question,

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              No. of matches they lost $= 3x$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              Total no. of matches $= 24$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              $ \begin{aligned} x + 3x &= 24 \\ 4x &= 24 \\ x &= \dfrac {24} {4} \\ &= \dfrac {6 \times 4} {4} \\ &= \dfrac {6 \times \cancel {4}} {\cancel {4}} \\ &= 6 \end{aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              They won $6$ matches.

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              $6$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              %empty%

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              %empty%

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                • $a + 2a + 4$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  $ \begin{aligned} &= a + 2a + 4 \\ &= 3a + 4 \end{aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  $3a + 4$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  • $4b - b + 5b$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    $ \begin{aligned} &= 4b - b + 5b \\ &= 8b \end{aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    $8b$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    • $2a + 2c + a + 4c$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      $ \begin{aligned} &= 2a + 2c + a + 4c \\ &= 3a + 6c \end{aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      $3a + 6c$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      • $x \times 2x \times 4d$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        $ \begin{aligned} &= x \times 2x \times 4d \\ &= 8 x ^2 d \end{aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        $8 x ^2 d$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        • $ab + 6b + 2ab$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          $ \begin{aligned} &= ab + 6b + 2ab \\ &= 3ab + 6b \\ &= 3b (a + 2) \end{aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          $3b (a + 2)$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          • $-3c \times 5ct + 2c \times 6$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                            $ \begin{aligned} &= -3c \times 5ct + 2c \times 6 \\ &= -15 c^2 t + 12 c \\ &= 3c (-5ct + 4c) \end{aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                            $3c (-5ct + 4c)$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  Cost of 1 steak = 84 \text{p}$ Cost of 5 Burgers = 84 x 5

To find out how many packs he bought, we have to divide these two numbers. 9.10 / 1.30 = 7 packs If James bought 7 packs and each pack has 8 sausages we know that he must have 56 sausages in total.

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    • Tyler buys $16$ chicken wings, and receives $\pounds 14.72$ change from a $\pounds 20$ note.

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      What is the price of a chicken wing?

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      16 Wings = $\pounds 5.28 16 / 1 Wing = $\pounds 5.28 / 16 1 Wing = $\pounds 0.33

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          Sara thinks of a number. She subtracts twelve, then divides by two and then adds fifteen. Her answer is $37$. What is the number that Sara first thought of?

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          Let the number $= a$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          As per the question,

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          $ \begin{aligned} \dfrac {a - 12} {2} + 15 &= 37 \\ \dfrac {a - 12} {2} &= 37 - 15 \\ \dfrac {a - 12} {2} &= 22 \\ a - 12 &= 22 \times 2 \\ a &= 44 + 12 \\ a &= 56 \end{aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          $56$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              Solve each of these equations below to find the value of $x$.

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              %empty%

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              %empty%

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                • $x - 4 = 17$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  $ \begin {aligned} x - 4 &= 17 \\ x &= 17 + 4 \\ x &= 21 \end {aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  $21$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  • $5x = 55$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    $ \begin {aligned} 5x &= 55 \\ x &= \dfrac {55} {5} \\ x &= 11 \end {aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    $11$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    • $\dfrac{x}{10} = 6$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      $ \begin {aligned} \dfrac {x} {10} &= 6 \\ x &= 6 \times 10 \\ x &= 60 \end {aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      $60$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      • $14 + x = 23$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        $ \begin {aligned} 14 + x &= 23 \\ x &= 23 - 14 \\ x &= 9 \end {aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        $9$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        • $\dfrac{1}{4}x = 7$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          $ \begin {aligned} \dfrac {1} {4} \x &= 7 \\ x &= 7 \times 4 \\ x &= 28 \end {aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          $28$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          • $7x = 37$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                            $ \begin {aligned} 7 \ x &= 37 \\ x &= \dfrac {37} {7} \\ x &= \dfrac {\cancel{37}} {\cancel{7}} \\ x &= 5.29 \end {aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                            $5.29$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          Solve the following two step , below, to find the value of $x$.

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          %empty%

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          %empty%

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                            • $5x - 9 = 6$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              $ \begin {aligned} 5x &= 9 + 6 \\ 5x &= 15 \\ x &= \dfrac {15} {5} \\ x &= 3 \end {aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              $3$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              • $\dfrac{x}{5} + 9 = 16$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                $ \begin {aligned} \dfrac {x} {5} + 9 &= 16 \\ 5 \times {\dfrac {x} {5}} + 5 \times 9 &= 5 \times 16 \\ \cancel{5} \times {\dfrac x {\cancel {5}}} + 45 &= 80 \\ x + 45 &= 80 \\ x &= 80 - 45 \\ x &= 35 \end {aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                $35$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                • $17 = 2 + 3x$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  $ \begin {aligned} 17 &= 2 + 3 x \\ 17 - 2 &= 3 x \\ 15 &= 3 \ x \\ x &= \dfrac {15} {3} \\ x &= \dfrac {5 \times 3} {3} \\ x &= \dfrac {5 \times \cancel {3}} { \cancel {3}} \\ x &= 5 \end {aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  $5$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  • $7x + 15 = 1$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    $ \begin {aligned} 7 x + 15 &= 1 \\ 7 x &= 1 - 15 \\ 7 x &= - 14 \\ x &=\dfrac {-14} {7} \\ x &= \dfrac {-2 \times 7} {7} \\ x &= \dfrac {-2 \times \cancel {7}} {\cancel {7}} \\ x &= - 2 \end {aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    $-2$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  • Tommy thinks of a number. When he doubles the number and then subtracts $11$, he gets the answer $17$. What was his number?

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    Let the number $= a$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    As per the question,

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    $ \begin{aligned} 2 \times a - 11 &= 17 \\ 2a &= 17 + 11 \\ 2a &= 28 \\ a &= \dfrac {28} {2} \\ a &= \dfrac {2 \times 14} {2} \\ a &= \dfrac {\cancel {2} \times 14} {\cancel {2}} \\ a &= 14 \end{aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    $14$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    • Lilly thinks of a number. When she takes away $11$ from the number and then doubles the answer, she gets $82$. What was her number?

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      Let the number $= a$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      As per the question,

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      $ \begin{aligned} 2 \times (a - 11) &= 82 \\ a - 11 &= \dfrac {82} {2} \\ a - 11 &= \dfrac {41 \times 2} {2} \\ a - 11 &= \dfrac {41 \times \cancel {2}} {\cancel {2}} \\ a - 11 &= 41 \\ a &= 41 + 11 \\ a &= 52 \end{aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      $52$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      • I’m thinking of a number. When I subtract the number from $45$, I get the same answer as when I double the number. What’s my number?

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        Let the number $= a$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        As per the question,

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        $ \begin{aligned} 45 - a &= 2 \times a \\ 45 &= 2 a + a \\ 45 &= 3 a \\ a &= \dfrac {45} {3} \\ a &= \dfrac {15 \times 3} {3} \\ a &= \dfrac {15 \times \cancel {3}} {\cancel {3}} \\ a &= 15 \\ \end{aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        $15$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      I think of a number.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       What’s my number?

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      A: $12$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      C: $8$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      D: $6$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      E: $9$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      As per the question,

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      $ \begin{aligned} 24 - a &= 2 \times a \\ 24 - a &= 2 a \\ 24 &= 2 a + a \\ 24 &= 3 a \\ 3 a &= 24 \\ a &= \dfrac {24} {3} \\ a &= \dfrac {8 \times 3} {3} \\ a &= \dfrac {8 \times \cancel{3}} {\cancel{3}} \\ a &= 8 \end{aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      C

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      $\text{Two-thirds}$ of a number is $3$ more than $\text{three-fifths}$ of the number. What’s the number?

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      A: $20$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      B: $90$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      D: $60$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      Let the number $= a$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      As per the question,

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      $ \begin{aligned} \dfrac {2} {3} \times a &= 3 + \dfrac {3} {5} \times a \\ \dfrac {2 a} {3} &= 3 + \dfrac {3 a} {5} \\ \dfrac {2 a} {3} - \dfrac {3 a} {5} &= 3 \\ \dfrac {2 a \times 5} {3 \times 5} - \dfrac {3 a \times 3} {5 \times 3} &= 3 \\ \dfrac {10 a} {15} - \dfrac {9 a} {15} &= 3 \\ \dfrac {10 a - 9 a} {15} &= 3 \\ \dfrac {a} {15} &= 3 \\ a &= 15 \times 3 \\ a &= 45 \end{aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      E

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      $45$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              • Sarah thinks of a number. When she triples the number and then adds $15$, she gets the answer $39$. What was her number?

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                Let the number $= a$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                As per the question,

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                $ \begin{aligned} 3 \times a + 15 &= 39 \\ 3 a &= 39 - 15 \\ 3 a &= 24 \\ a &= \dfrac {24} {3} \\ a &= \dfrac {8 \times 3} {3} \\ a &= \dfrac {8 \times \cancel {3}} {\cancel {3}} \\ a &= 8 \end{aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                $8$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                • Kirsty thinks of a number. When she adds $15$ to the number and then triples the answer, she gets $39$. What was her number?

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  Let the number $= a$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  As per the question,

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  $ \begin{aligned} 3 \times (a + 15) &= 39 \\ a + 15 &= \dfrac {39} {3} \\ a + 15 &= \dfrac {13 \times 3} {3} \\ a + 15 &= \dfrac {13 \times \cancel {3}} {\cancel {3}} \\ a + 15 &= 13 \\ a &= 13 - 15 \\ a &= - 2 \end{aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  $-2$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  • Zack thinks of a number. When he triples the number and subtracts the answer from $71$, he gets one more than double his original number. What was his number?

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    Let the number $= a$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    As per the question,

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    $ \begin{aligned} 71 - 3 \times a &= 1 + 2 \times a \\ 71 - 1 &= 2 a + 3 a \\ 70 &= 5 a \\ 5 a &= 70 \\ a &= \dfrac {70} {5} \\ a &= \dfrac {14 \times 5} {5} \\ a &= \dfrac {14 \times \cancel {5}} {\cancel {5}} \\ a &= 14 \end{aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    $14$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  I think of a number, multiply it by $\text{three}$ and add $7$. The answer is $25$. What is the number I am thinking of?

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  Let the number $= a$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  As per the question,

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  $ \begin{aligned} 3 \times a + 7 &= 25 \\ 3 a + 7 &= 25 \\ 3 a &= 25 - 7 \\ 3 a &= 18 \\ a &= \dfrac {18} {3} \\ a &= \dfrac {6 \times 3} {3} \\ a &= \dfrac {6 \times \cancel {3}} {\cancel {3}} \\ a &= 6 \end{aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  $6$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  A school are collecting tokens for ‘free books’. Sarah brings $28$ tokens to school. Leena brings $13$ less than Sarah and Jane brings in $7$ more than Sarah.

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  %empty%

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      \end{aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        \end{aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      In each of the following statements $N$ stands for a number.

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      Write down the value of $N$ which makes each of the statements true.

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      %empty%

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      %empty%

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        • $7 + N = 13$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          $ \begin{aligned} 7 + N &= 13 \\ N &= 13 - 7 \\ N &= 6 \end{aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          $6$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          • $4 \times N = 36$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                            $ \begin{aligned} 4 \times N &= 36 \\ N &= \dfrac {36} {4} \\ N &= \dfrac {9 \times \cancel {4}} {\cancel {4}} \\ N &= 9 \end{aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                            $9$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                            • $N \times N = 25$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              $ \begin{aligned} N \times N &= 25 \\ N ^ 2 &= 25 \\ N &= \sqrt {25} \\ N &= 5 \end{aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              $5$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              • $N - 6 = N \div 2$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                $ \begin{aligned} N - 6 &= N \div 2 \\ N - 6 &= \dfrac {N} {2} \\ 2(N - 6) &= N \\ 2N - 12 &= N \\ 2N - N &= 12 \\ N &= 12 \end{aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                $12$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                • $3y + 1 = 16$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    $ \begin{aligned} 18 &= 4k + 6 \\ 18 - 6 &= 4k \\ 4k &= 12 \\ k &= \dfrac {12} {4} \\ k &= \dfrac {4 \times 3} {4} \\ k &= \dfrac {\cancel {4} \times 3} {\cancel {4}} \\ k &= 3 \end{aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    $3$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              • $b + 4 = a$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                $ \begin{aligned} b + 4 &= a \\ b &= a - 4 \end{aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                $a - 4$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                • $4d = c$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  $ \begin{aligned} 4d &= c \\ d &= \dfrac {c} {4} \end{aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  $\dfrac {c} {4}$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  • $m - 3 = 4k$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    $ \begin{aligned} m - 3 &= 4k \\ m &= 4k +3 \end{aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    $4k +3$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      $ \begin{aligned} t ^ 2 &= 4s \\ 4s &= t ^ 2 \\ s &= \dfrac {t ^ 2} {4} \end{aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          I think of a number and multiply it by $3$ and then subtract $6$. If the result is $15$ what number was I thinking of?

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          Let the number $= a$

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          As per the question,

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          $ \begin{aligned} a \times 3 - 6 &= 15 \\ 3 a - 6 &= 15 \\ 3 a &= 15 + 6 \\ 3 a &= 21 \\ a &= \dfrac {21} {3} \\ a &= \dfrac {3 \times 7} {3} \\ a &= \dfrac {\cancel {3} \times 7} {\cancel {3}} \\ a &= 7 \end{aligned} $

                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          $7$
